ze=1> I don't know about other countries but I do know as a US citizen what I pay in taxes.<br>
SO here it is...<br>
<br>
28% Fed income tax, 15% for social (in)security (half that is paid by employer but if you are self employed you pay all of it)<br>
3% Illinois state income tax (which is low as state tax goes). That adds up to 46% income tax. Compare that to 50% listed for countries in a previous post. That is a 4% difference and most of those countries have socialized medicine.<br>
<br>
Bet you the US government cant give us socialized medicine for only a 4% increase. Not to mention that I can not count on the 15% taken from me as social security to be there when I retire since the government has looted the fund. SO that sounds like government is very inefficient in the US.<br>
<br>
By the way the tax does not just stop at 46%. My state I pay 7% sales tax. So assuming I have to spend everything I earn to survive I pay 53% tax. Even if I don't spend it and save it for a rainy day I will pay tax on the interest which is worse since part of the interest is negated by inflation. Sure seems like a lot to me. <br>
<br>
I understand pure socialism to be the equivalent of 100% tax. Everything goes to the government and the government parses it back out. We know that does not work because it is a productivity disincentive due to human nature of doing the least possible to obtain the same results. By this I mean if I work harder than my neighbor but receive the same amount of reward I will stop working as hard. I like to think of it as &quot;slavery to the state&quot;. I work where, when, how they want me to for an unnegotiable reward. <br>
<br>
Capitalism is basically the opposite. The problem with capitalism without ethics it can leads to abuse with a few taking more of a share than they deserve. Thus we need a good system of laws and courts and yes things like unions to<br>
protect people.<br>
<br>
Democrats in the US seem to be more in favor of a strong socialistic system (Federal institutions) but still maintaining a capitalistic system as a tax base to fund it. Problem it depends on the ethics of those in government to distribute the money fairly, not waste it, etc. A system that requires less planning on the part of an individual to secure their current  and future needs since most everything is taken care of.<br>
And if it is social reform you want I don't think governments can do it. Tolerance and understanding of others can only come from teaching it.<br>
<br>
Republicans tend more toward capitalism but as I believe still some elements of socialism such as limited help for those most in need. Involves a lot of personal risk and responsible to provide for ones needs. Note I am against the Farm aid since it does not follow this premise. <br>
<br>
I see both as hybrids a combination of socialism and capitalism. The quest is the degree of each.<br>
<br>
Ideally we want a social system that can provide the basic needs for everyone but allow you to obtain nicer things by working hard. People need the incentive of being able to get nicer things to keep productivity high. If productivity is high and there is little waste in government allocated money you can keep taxes low and provide the basic needs. Here is an important point between Rep and Democrat on that issue. You don't need the government to provide all the basic needs, you only need the means of obtaining them i.e. have enough money to buy the service. A lot of Rep believe the government is inefficient so the money should be returned to the people (lower taxes) after which they can get the service at a more competitive rate with more options for the private sector.<br>
